## Why This Is Asked

Assess familiarity with Linux process scheduling, cgroups, systemd properties, and practical experimentation. The scenario emphasizes beginner-friendly diagnostic steps and safe rollback.

## Key Concepts

- Linux CPU scheduling basics (CFS, CPU shares vs quotas)
- Systemd resource controls (CPUQuota, CPUQuotaPeriodUSec, cpuset)
- Tools: mpstat, pidstat, iostat, systemd-cgls

## Code Example

```javascript
#!/usr/bin/env node
const {execSync} = require('child_process');
const services = ['critical-api', 'worker-a'];
services.forEach(s=>{
  try{
    const quota = execSync(`systemctl show ${s} -p CPUQuota --value`, {encoding:'utf8'}).trim();
    const per = execSync(`systemctl show ${s} -p CPUQuotaPeriodUSec --value`, {encoding:'utf8'}).trim();
    console.log(`${s}: CPUQuota=${quota||'0'}, PeriodUSec=${per||'0'}`);
  }catch(e){
    console.error(`err ${s}:`, e.message);
  }
});
```

## Follow-up Questions

- Which steps would you automate to monitor for burst-induced latency and what signals would you alert on?
- What trade-offs exist between CPUQuota vs cpuset in terms of scheduling fairness and contention?

## Why This Is Asked

Real-time network paths require precise tail latency insight without burdening performance. eBPF offers low-overhead, per-event visibility ideal for diagnosing bursts in UDP data paths.

## Key Concepts

- eBPF tracing (bpftrace/bpfcc) for live latency data
- Tracepoints vs kprobes for kernel events
- Per-CPU histograms and BPF maps for aggregation
- Data-path isolation with tc and minimal instrumentation
- Safe rollback/guardrails if overhead grows

## Code Example

```javascript
function percentile(arr, p){
  if (!arr.length) return 0;
  const sorted = [...arr].sort((a,b)=>a-b);
  const idx = Math.ceil((sorted.length-1)*p/100);
  return sorted[idx];
}
```

## Follow-up Questions

- How would you adapt this plan if TLS/DTLS terminates before the RX path?
- What thresholds and sampling rates would you choose for a fleet of hosts, and how would you automate rollback across them?
